  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "One Head Is Not Enough"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A single attention head produces one weighted blend of value vectors per position. But natural language has many types of relationships between words simultaneously: grammatical agreement, coreference, semantic similarity, positional proximity. A single head cannot specialise in all of them at once. Multi-head attention runs "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "h independent attention heads in parallel"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", each free to learn a different attention pattern, then merges their outputs."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "How Multi-Head Attention Works"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Each head i has its own learned projection matrices W_Qⁱ, W_Kⁱ, W_Vⁱ. The head projects the input into a lower-dimensional subspace and runs standard scaled dot-product attention:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{head}_i = \\text{Attention}(X W_Q^i,\\; X W_K^i,\\; X W_V^i)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The h outputs are concatenated and projected back to d_model via an output weight W_O:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{MultiHead}(Q,K,V) = \\text{Concat}(\\text{head}_1,\\ldots,\\text{head}_h)\\, W_O"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Multi-head attention architecture showing h parallel heads each with separate Q/K/V projections, concatenation, and output projection W_O"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Dimensions and Parameter Count"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "To keep total compute similar to a single large head, each head is given a reduced dimension:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "d_k = d_v = \\frac{d_{\\text{model}}}{h}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For BERT-base: d_model = 768, h = 12, so d_k = 64. The weight matrices per head are W_Qⁱ ∈ ℝ^(d_model × d_k), W_Kⁱ ∈ ℝ^(d_model × d_k), W_Vⁱ ∈ ℝ^(d_model × d_v). Together with W_O ∈ ℝ^(h·d_v × d_model), the total parameter count is:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "3h \\cdot d_{\\text{model}} \\cdot d_k \\;+\\; h \\cdot d_v \\cdot d_{\\text{model}} = 4 \\cdot d_{\\text{model}}^2"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This is the same as a single attention head with d_k = d_model — the split into heads adds representational diversity without increasing parameter count."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Implementation from Scratch"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\nimport math\n\nclass MultiHeadAttention(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, d_model: int, num_heads: int):\n        super().__init__()\n        assert d_model % num_heads == 0, \"d_model must be divisible by num_heads\"\n        self.h = num_heads\n        self.d_k = d_model // num_heads\n\n        # One linear layer per projection, but we pack all heads together\n        # W_Q, W_K, W_V each: (d_model → d_model) covering all heads at once\n        self.W_Q = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model, bias=False)\n        self.W_K = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model, bias=False)\n        self.W_V = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model, bias=False)\n        self.W_O = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model, bias=False)\n\n    def split_heads(self, x):\n        \"\"\"(batch, seq, d_model) → (batch, heads, seq, d_k)\"\"\"\n        batch, seq, d_model = x.shape\n        x = x.view(batch, seq, self.h, self.d_k)\n        return x.transpose(1, 2)  # (batch, heads, seq, d_k)\n\n    def forward(self, Q, K, V, mask=None):\n        \"\"\"\n        Q, K, V: (batch, seq, d_model)\n        mask:    optional (batch, 1, seq, seq) boolean or additive mask\n        \"\"\"\n        # Project and split into heads\n        Q = self.split_heads(self.W_Q(Q))  # (batch, h, seq, d_k)\n        K = self.split_heads(self.W_K(K))\n        V = self.split_heads(self.W_V(V))\n\n        # Scaled dot-product attention per head\n        scores = torch.matmul(Q, K.transpose(-2, -1)) / math.sqrt(self.d_k)\n        if mask is not None:\n            scores = scores + mask  # additive mask; -inf for blocked positions\n        attn_weights = F.softmax(scores, dim=-1)  # (batch, h, seq, seq)\n\n        # Weighted sum of values\n        context = torch.matmul(attn_weights, V)   # (batch, h, seq, d_k)\n\n        # Concatenate heads and project\n        batch, h, seq, d_k = context.shape\n        context = context.transpose(1, 2).contiguous().view(batch, seq, h * d_k)\n        return self.W_O(context), attn_weights  # (batch, seq, d_model)\n\n# Demo\nbatch, seq, d_model, num_heads = 2, 10, 512, 8\nmha = MultiHeadAttention(d_model, num_heads)\nx = torch.randn(batch, seq, d_model)\nout, attn = mha(x, x, x)   # self-attention: Q = K = V = x\nprint(out.shape)    # (2, 10, 512)\nprint(attn.shape)   # (2, 8, 10, 10) — one matrix per head"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Using PyTorch's Built-in Module"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\n\n# nn.MultiheadAttention(embed_dim, num_heads, batch_first=True)\nmha = nn.MultiheadAttention(embed_dim=512, num_heads=8, batch_first=True)\n\nbatch, seq, d_model = 2, 10, 512\nx = torch.randn(batch, seq, d_model)\n\n# Self-attention: query = key = value = x\n# need_weights=False skips materialising the attention matrix (faster)\nout, attn_weights = mha(x, x, x, need_weights=True)\nprint(out.shape)          # (2, 10, 512)\nprint(attn_weights.shape) # (2, 10, 10) — averaged across heads by default\n\n# For decoder self-attention (causal mask)\ncausal_mask = nn.Transformer.generate_square_subsequent_mask(seq)\nout_causal, _ = mha(x, x, x, attn_mask=causal_mask)\nprint(out_causal.shape)   # (2, 10, 512)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
