      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Visualising Per-Head Attention"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModel\nimport torch\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n\ntokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased')\nmodel = AutoModel.from_pretrained('bert-base-uncased', output_attentions=True)\n\ntext = \"She saw the man with the telescope\"\ninputs = tokenizer(text, return_tensors='pt')\n\nwith torch.no_grad():\n    out = model(**inputs)\n\n# out.attentions: tuple of (batch, num_heads, seq, seq), one per layer\nlayer5 = out.attentions[5][0]   # (12 heads, seq, seq)\ntokens = tokenizer.convert_ids_to_tokens(inputs['input_ids'][0])\n\nfig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 4, figsize=(14, 9))\nfor i, ax in enumerate(axes.flat):\n    ax.imshow(layer5[i].numpy(), cmap='Blues', vmin=0, vmax=1)\n    ax.set_title(f'Head {i+1}', fontsize=8)\n    ax.set_xticks(range(len(tokens))); ax.set_xticklabels(tokens, rotation=45, fontsize=6)\n    ax.set_yticks(range(len(tokens))); ax.set_yticklabels(tokens, fontsize=6)\nplt.suptitle('Layer 5 — 12 heads, BERT-base')\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Role of W_O"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "After concatenation, each head's output occupies a separate block of the h·d_v-dimensional vector. W_O is a learned linear map that "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "mixes information across heads"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and projects back to d_model. Without W_O, the heads would be independent and the output space would be partitioned rather than fused. W_O lets the model learn how to weight and combine each head's perspective into a single unified representation."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "bold"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "Key insight:"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " Multi-head attention is cheaper than it sounds. Because each head uses d_k = d_model/h, the total FLOPs are identical to a single head at d_model. The cost is the same; the benefit is representational diversity across h subspaces."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
